description:
The third wave of Human–Computer Interaction (HCI) brings increased attention to the social, ethical, and cultural dimensions of technology design. Within this paradigm, researchers and practitioners are called upon to address—and critically reflect on—implicit assumptions about users and contexts of use. However, while reflection is widely recognised as essential for responsible and inclusive design, there remains a lack of systematic support for integrating reflective practices into everyday HCI work.

This thesis proposes to develop and evaluate a means of supporting reflection in technology design projects. The research pursues three main objectives:

Conceptual Exploration – to examine key concepts such as implicit assumptions and reflection, and to provide an overview of existing approaches to reflection in human–technology interaction and related fields;

Empirical Investigation – to analyse feedback from HCI practitioners regarding challenges and needs related to reflective practice;

Methodological Contribution – to design and evaluate a structured framework and an accompanying digital tool that facilitate reflection within the design process.
